1

00:00:00,000  -->  00:00:02,605
Which makes sense up there.

2

00:00:02,605  -->  00:00:08,200
This is like fulfilling a small order where you know exactly how many cookies you need.

3

00:00:08,200  -->  00:00:13,260
Sometimes however, you may not know how many batches of cookies you'll need to bake.

4

00:00:13,260  -->  00:00:16,360
Maybe orders keep coming in throughout the day,

5

00:00:16,360  -->  00:00:18,080
and you just need to keep baking,

6

00:00:18,080  -->  00:00:20,920
but keep track of how many cookies you're baking.

7

00:00:20,920  -->  00:00:23,940
In this case, you can skip specifying a limit,

8

00:00:23,940  -->  00:00:26,500
allowing the generator to run indefinitely.

9

00:00:26,500  -->  00:00:31,580
This time, we'll initialize a new generator object that has a batch size of 100,

10

00:00:31,580  -->  00:00:36,400
but no Max batches parameter as the input like this,

11

00:00:36,400  -->  00:00:47,410
which you'll see right here, unlimited_cookie_batches = bake_cookies(100).

12

00:00:48,800  -->  00:00:53,070
This will allow us to run this generator function as many times

13

00:00:53,070  -->  00:00:56,970
as we'd like to. We'll initialize this.

14

00:00:56,970  -->  00:01:00,770
Then every time we run the generator on this new generator object,

15

00:01:00,770  -->  00:01:05,590
we get outputs that count upwards beyond 300.

16

00:01:05,590  -->  00:01:09,990
For example, taking the unlimited_cookie_batches with next,

17

00:01:09,990  -->  00:01:13,800
we'll run the cell, and we see 100.

18

00:01:13,800  -->  00:01:18,920
Next, we see 200, next, we see 300,

19

00:01:18,920  -->  00:01:21,130
and now we see past 300,

20

00:01:21,130  -->  00:01:25,180
400, 500, and so on.

21

00:01:25,180  -->  00:01:31,390
With no limit. You control when to stop by simply deciding when to

22

00:01:31,390  -->  00:01:37,790
stop calling the next function on our unlimited_cookie_batches generator object.

23

00:01:37,790  -->  00:01:40,590
This is useful if you want to keep the bakery

24

00:01:40,590  -->  00:01:44,455
running until you decide to close shop for the day.

25

00:01:44,455  -->  00:01:48,440
Let's quickly review what we learned about functions and generators.

26

00:01:48,440  -->  00:01:51,300
Functions are versatile tools that allow us

27

00:01:51,300  -->  00:01:54,400
to execute a block of code with a specific purpose.

28

00:01:54,400  -->  00:01:56,080
They can take in parameters,

29

00:01:56,080  -->  00:01:58,940
perform actions, and return a result.

30

00:01:58,940  -->  00:02:03,420
Functions are great for performing one off tasks or calculations all at once.

31

00:02:03,420  -->  00:02:05,900
However, they return a single result and

32

00:02:05,900  -->  00:02:08,685
don't retain any state after they finish executing.

33

00:02:08,685  -->  00:02:13,830
Some examples can be built-in functions that Python all ready comes preloaded with,

34

00:02:13,830  -->  00:02:19,730
or we can write our own self defined functions to handle our own custom logic.

35

00:02:19,730  -->  00:02:21,370
Generators, on the other hand,

36

00:02:21,370  -->  00:02:24,330
are a special type of function that lets you control

37

00:02:24,330  -->  00:02:27,890
the flow of production in a more gradual way.

38

00:02:27,890  -->  00:02:30,250
By using yield instead of return,

39

00:02:30,250  -->  00:02:33,910
generators produce values one at a time,

40

00:02:33,910  -->  00:02:37,830
pausing between each until they're needed again.

41

00:02:37,830  -->  00:02:40,310
This is like baking cookies in batches.

42

00:02:40,310  -->  00:02:44,650
You only bake what you need when you need it, which saves resources.

43

00:02:44,650  -->  00:02:47,340
Generators are ideal for handling

44

00:02:47,340  -->  00:02:51,920
large sequences or ongoing tasks without overloading memory.

45

00:02:51,920  -->  00:02:54,660
Instead of holding all the data at once,

46

00:02:54,660  -->  00:02:57,020
they create each piece as requested.

47

00:02:57,020  -->  00:03:00,960
This is incredibly useful for scenarios where you might not know

48

00:03:00,960  -->  00:03:05,505
the total size of the data or want to process it in chunks.

49

00:03:05,505  -->  00:03:11,955
In summary, functions are great for one off or repeatable execution of the same code,

50

00:03:11,955  -->  00:03:15,530
while generators give you flexibility and efficiency,

51

00:03:15,530  -->  00:03:17,490
yielding items on demand.

52

00:03:17,490  -->  00:03:22,830
This makes them perfect for tasks where you want to manage resources carefully and work

53

00:03:22,830  -->  00:03:29,220
with large or continuous data streams one manageable batch at a time.
